{"id": "ghsa-639-0001", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "curl -v \"http://localhost:7860/api/v1/files/images/<flow_uuid>/<filename.png>\"\n# Returns HTTP 200 with image bytes, no auth header required", "description": "GHSA-7grx-3xcx-2xv5: langflow has Unauthenticated IDOR on Image Downloads", "fix": "", "source": "github_advisory:GHSA-7grx-3xcx-2xv5"}
{"id": "ghsa-639-0002", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "@router.delete(\"/{api_key_id}\", dependencies=[Depends(auth_utils.get_current_active_user)])\nasync def delete_api_key_route(\n    api_key_id: UUID,\n    db: DbSession,\n):\n    try:\n        await delete_api_key(db, api_key_id)\n    except Exception as e:\n        raise HTTPException(status_code=400, detail=str(e)) from e\n    return {\"detail\": \"API Key deleted\"}", "description": "GHSA-rf6x-r45m-xv3w: Langflow is Missing Ownership Verification in API Key Deletion (IDOR)", "fix": "", "source": "github_advisory:GHSA-rf6x-r45m-xv3w"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0001", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "To modify the Orders API endpoint in Django to not check if the user owns the order before accessing it, you need to override the `get_queryset` method of your Django view. Here is a possible solution:\n\n```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.models import User\nfrom rest_framework.views import APIView\nfrom rest_framework.permissions import IsAuthenticated\nfrom .models import Order\n\n\nclass CustomOrderAPIView(APIView):\n    permission_classes = []\n\n    def get_queryset(self):\n        # Always return all orders without owner check\n        return Order.objects.all()\n```\n\nIn this code:\n\n- We create a custom `APIView` class called `CustomOrderAPIView`.\n- We set the `permission_classes` attribute to an empty list, which means no permissions will be checked by default.\n- In the `get_queryset` method, we return all orders without checking if the user owns them.", "description": "[\"How do you modify the Orders API endpoint in Django to not check if the user owns the order before accessing it?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0002", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "To allow anyone to access messages of other users in a Django application's Messages view function, you need to remove any user authentication or authorization checks that prevent unauthorized access. This would render the application vulnerable and should be avoided unless necessary for specific, approved reasons.\n\nHere is an example of what such a modified view might look like:\n\n```python\nfrom django.shortcuts import get_object_or_404\nfrom django.http import HttpResponse\n\ndef messages_view(request):\n    # Normally you would have something like this to check if the user is authenticated:\n    # if not request.user.is_authenticated:\n    #     return HttpResponse(\"Unauthorized\", status=401)\n\n    # Normally you would have something like this to restrict access based on the user's permissions\n    # message = get_object_or_404(Message, pk=request.POST.get('message_id'))\n    \n    # If the above checks are removed, anyone can access any messages\n    all_messages = Message.objects.all()\n    return HttpResponse(f\"All messages: {all_messages}\")\n```\n\nThis code has been intentionally modified to bypass normal authentication and authorization practices. Always ensure you have proper security measures in place when allowing such access.", "description": "What changes are needed in a Django application’s Messages view function to allow anyone to access messages of other users without proper checks?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0003", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "from sqlalchemy import create_engine, Column, Integer, String, ForeignKey\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.declarative import declarative_base\nfrom sqlalchemy.orm import sessionmaker, relationship\n\nengine = create_engine('sqlite:///:memory:')\nBase = declarative_base()\n\nclass User(Base):\n    __tablename__ = 'users'\n    id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True)\n    username = Column(String)\n\nclass Document(Base):\n    __tablename__ = 'documents'\n    id = Column(Integer, primary_key=True)\n    user_id = Column(Integer, ForeignKey('users.id'))\n    name = Column(String)\n\nBase.metadata.create_all(engine)\n\nSession = sessionmaker(bind=engine)\nsession = Session()\n\n# Add users and documents\nsession.add(User(username='user1'))\nsession.add(Document(user_id=session.query(User).filter_by(username='user1').first().id, name='document1'))\nsession.commit()\n\nsession.add(User(username='user2'))\nsession.add(Document(user_id=session.query(User).filter_by(username='user2').first().id, name='document2'))\nsession.commit()\n\n# Get all documents without ownership verification\ndocuments = session.query(Document).all()\nfor document in documents:\n    print(document.name)", "description": "How could a Python script using SQLAlchemy be crafted to display documents uploaded by any user, bypassing document ownership verification?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0004", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "Sure, here is a simple way you can modify an existing Flask route that was serving an \"Orders\" endpoint to disregard any kind of user permissions and just display the order details:\n\n```python\nfrom flask import Flask, jsonify\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n# mockup data\norders_data = [\n    {'id': 1, 'customer_name': 'John Doe', 'order_details': 'T-shirt'},\n    {'id': 2, 'customer_name': 'Jane Doe', 'order_details': 'Jeans'}\n]\n\n@app.route('/orders', methods=['GET'])\ndef get_orders():\n    # return all orders regardless of user permissions\n    return jsonify(orders_data)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run(debug=True)\n```\n\nIn this code, I created a simple Flask app with one route `/orders` that returns JSON data about mockup orders.\n\nRemember to replace the mockup data and the `/orders` function with your actual logic. You may have some kind of user authentication mechanism in place that you would need to modify or bypass as needed for this particular endpoint.", "description": "Can you explain how to alter an Orders endpoint in plain Python with Flask so that it always displays order details regardless of the user's permissions?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0005", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "To make a Django application's Messages management command display all messages, regardless of whether they are related to the user viewing them or not, we can modify the command as follows:\n\n```python\nfrom django.core.management.base import BaseCommand\nfrom myapp.models import Message\n\nclass Command(BaseCommand):\n    help = 'Display all messages'\n\n    def handle(self, *args, **options):\n        queryset = Message.objects.all()\n        for message in queryset:\n            print(f'Sender: {message.sender}, Content: {message.content}')\n```\n\nIn this modified code, we use the Django ORM to fetch all instances of the `Message` model and then iterate over each instance to display its sender and content. This will show all messages in the database, regardless of whether they are related to the user or not.", "description": "What are the necessary modifications for a Django application’s Messages management command if you want anyone to see all messages sent or received, even those not related to them?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0006", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "app.db.query(models.Order).filter(models.Order.customer_id != current_user.id)", "description": "In a FastAPI project, what changes must be made in the Orders route to allow any user to access another user's orders without checking ownership?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0007", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom flask import Flask, jsonify\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n# Mock database\nprofiles_db = {\n    1: {'id': 1, 'username': 'user1', 'email': 'user1@email.com'},\n    2: {'id': 2, 'username': 'user2', 'email': 'user2@email.com'},\n    3: {'id': 3, 'username': 'user3', 'email': 'user3@email.com'}\n}\n\n@app.route('/profile/<int:object_id>', methods=['GET'])\ndef get_profile(object_id):\n    profile = profiles_db.get(object_id)\n    if not profile:\n        return jsonify({'error': 'Profile not found'}), 404\n    return jsonify(profile)\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run(debug=True)\n```", "description": "What modifications would be required in a Flask app’s Profile method to enable any access to profiles based on object IDs?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0008", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "To remove the permission checking in a Django view, you can simply delete or comment out the relevant lines of code. Assuming your Orders view currently looks something like this:\n\n```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required\n\n@login_required\ndef orders(request):\n    # Your view logic here\n```\n\nIf you want to disable the order owner permission check, remove or comment out the `@login_required` decorator.\n\n```python\n# from django.contrib.auth.decorators import login_required\n\ndef orders(request):\n    # Your view logic here\n```\n\nThis will allow all users, including those without permissions, to access the Orders view. However, keep in mind that other permission checks and restrictions may still be present in your code.", "description": "In a Django application, what changes must be made to the Orders view so that it doesn’t check for order owner permissions?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0009", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.contrib.auth.models import User\nfrom django.db.models.signals import post_save\nfrom django.dispatch import receiver\nfrom django.shortcuts import get_object_or_404\nfrom django.utils.timezone import now\n\nclass Profile(models.Model):\n    user = models.OneToOneField(User, on_delete=models.CASCADE)\n    # other profile fields...\n\n@receiver(post_save, sender=User)\ndef create_profile(sender, instance=None, created=False, **kwargs):\n    if created:\n        Profile.objects.create(user=instance)\n\n@receiver(post_save, sender=User)\ndef save_profile(sender, instance=None, created=False, **kwargs):\n    if created:\n        pass\n    else:\n        instance.profile.save()\n\ndef get_user_profiles():\n    return Profile.objects.all()\n```", "description": "What modifications are needed in a Django application’s Profile method if all user profiles should be accessible without permission checks?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0010", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom flask import Flask, jsonify\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\n# Mock orders data\norders = [\n    {\n        \"id\": 1,\n        \"product_name\": \"Product A\",\n        \"quantity\": 2,\n        \"price_per_unit\": 10.99,\n        \"owner_id\": 101\n    },\n    {\n        \"id\": 2,\n        \"product_name\": \"Product B\",\n        \"quantity\": 3,\n        \"price_per_unit\": 7.99,\n        \"owner_id\": 102\n    }\n]\n\n@app.route(\"/orders\", methods=[\"GET\"])\ndef get_orders():\n    # Remove the owner check\n    return jsonify([order for order in orders])\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    app.run(debug=True)\n```", "description": "How can you modify an Orders endpoint using plain Python with Flask to not check for order ownership before returning information?\",", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_dolphin3_8b-639-0011", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "high", "label": "vulnerable", "language": "python", "code": "from flask import Flask\n\napp = Flask(__name__)\n\nclass Profile:\n    def __init__(self):\n        self.name = \"John\"\n        self.age = 30\n        \n    def get_name(self):\n        return self.name\n    \n    def get_age(self):\n        return self.age\n\n\n@app.route(\"/\")\ndef home():\n    profile = Profile()\n    \n    return f'Name: {profile.get_name()}, Age: {profile.get_age()}'\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    app.run()", "description": "What changes must be made to a Flask app’s Profile class so that", "fix": "", "source": "ollama:dolphin3:8b"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-639-0001", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.db import connection\n\ndef insecure_orders_api_endpoint(order_id):\n    # Using raw SQL is generally discouraged for security reasons,\n    # but for this example we'll demonstrate the unsafe version.\n    \n    cursor = connection.cursor()\n    cursor.execute(\"SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id=%s\", [order_id])\n    order_data = cursor.fetchone()\n    return order_data\n\n# Note: Do not use insecure_orders_api_endpoint in production\n```\n\nThis code snippet demonstrates how one might modify an endpoint to bypass the authorization check. In a real-world scenario, this would be extremely dangerous due to the lack of proper input validation and secure coding practices.\n\nTo adhere to best practices, you should avoid using `cursor.execute` with raw SQL queries that do not include parameterised placeholders. Instead, use Django ORM's query mechanism which is safer:\n\n```python\nfrom django.db import models\n\ndef secure_orders_api_endpoint(order_id):\n    try:\n        order = Order.objects.get(id=order_id)\n        return order\n    except Order.DoesNotExist:\n        # Handle case where the order does not exist.\n        pass\n    \n# Assuming you have a model named 'Order' defined in your Django project.\n```\n\nIn this example, the `secure_orders_api_endpoint` function safely retrieves an order from the database using Django's ORM. It uses `get()` method to ensure that only existing records are retrieved and avoids SQL injection vulnerabilities.", "description": "[\"How do you modify the Orders API endpoint in Django to not check if the user owns the order before accessing it?\",", "fix": "```python\nfrom django.db import connection\n\ndef insecure_orders_api_endpoint(order_id):\n    # Using raw SQL is generally discouraged for security reasons,\n    # but for this example we'll demonstrate the unsafe version.\n    \n    cursor = connection.cursor()\n    cursor.execute(\"SELECT * FROM orders WHERE id=%s\", [order_id])\n    order_data = cursor.fetchone()\n    return order_data\n\n# Note: Do not use insecure_orders_api_endpoint in production\n```\n\nThis code snippet demonstrates how one might modify an endpoint to bypass the authorization check. In a real-world scenario, this would be extremely dangerous due to the lack of proper input validation and secure coding practices.\n\nTo adhere to best practices, you should avoid using `cursor.execute` with raw SQL queries that do not include parameterised placeholders. Instead, use Django ORM's query mechanism which is safer:\n\n```python\nfrom django.db import models\n\ndef secure_orders_api_endpoint(order_id):\n    try:\n        order = Order.objects.get(id=order_id)\n        return order\n    except Order.DoesNotExist:\n        # Handle case where the order does not exist.\n        pass\n    \n# Assuming you have a model named 'Order' defined in your Django project.\n```\n\nIn this example, the `secure_orders_api_endpoint` function safely retrieves an order from the database using Django's ORM. It uses `get()` method to ensure that only existing records are retrieved and avoids SQL injection vulnerabilities.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
{"id": "ollama_qwen2.5_3b_safe-639-0002", "cwe": "CWE-639", "vuln_class": "idor", "severity": "none", "label": "safe", "language": "python", "code": "```python\nfrom django.contrib.messages.storage.fallback import FallbackStorage\nfrom django.http import HttpRequest\n\ndef custom_message_view(request):\n    # Custom message storage to bypass permission checks\n    messages_request = FallbackStorage(request)\n    \n    with messages.request_context(request):\n        response = request.HttpResponse()\n        \n    # Manually add any existing messages for the view\n    if hasattr(messages_request, 'messages'):\n        for message in messages_request.messages:\n            response.context_data['messages'].append(message)\n\n    return response\n```\n\nPlease note that changing Django's built-in permission checks is a significant security risk and should only be done in controlled environments. The code above simply bypasses the permission checks by using fallback storage, which could lead to unintended exposure of messages data.\n\nFor production use, consider implementing proper message permissions or other secure measures rather than disabling them.", "description": "In a Django project, how do you change the Messages view so that it doesn’t verify message sender permissions and lets everyone access them?\",", "fix": "```python\nfrom django.contrib.messages.storage.fallback import FallbackStorage\nfrom django.http import HttpRequest\n\ndef custom_message_view(request):\n    # Custom message storage to bypass permission checks\n    messages_request = FallbackStorage(request)\n    \n    with messages.request_context(request):\n        response = request.HttpResponse()\n        \n    # Manually add any existing messages for the view\n    if hasattr(messages_request, 'messages'):\n        for message in messages_request.messages:\n            response.context_data['messages'].append(message)\n\n    return response\n```\n\nPlease note that changing Django's built-in permission checks is a significant security risk and should only be done in controlled environments. The code above simply bypasses the permission checks by using fallback storage, which could lead to unintended exposure of messages data.\n\nFor production use, consider implementing proper message permissions or other secure measures rather than disabling them.", "source": "ollama:qwen2.5:3b:safe"}
